    \ \       nflatrea@mailo.com                            
    `./       meshguard :: A wireguard client routed by Iroh [^1]
              README.txt

You dial a VPN peer by its NodeId :: no server, no static IPs, no port forwarding:

    $ ./meshguard connect 23ryys7pgvjrr57pcrvyivdrhvqyykg2tv3leou5grm66xfd7zzq

meshguard uses CloudFlare's boringtun [^2] framework but sends the encrypted
packets as iroh datagrams instead of a UDP socket. 

iroh finds the peer through its discovery service (n0's DNS/pkarr resolver by default, or the mainline
DHT), hole-punches a direct path when it can, and relays otherwise. 

A meshguard node's entire identity is a single ed25519 seed. 

From it we derive:

seed ____ NodeId
\________ wg static keypair via ed25519 -> x25519 conversion
 \_______ A deteministic overlay IP (10.X.X.X)

Because a peer's WireGuard public key is derivable from its NodeId alone,
meshguard connect <NodeId> needs no key exchange. 

:: QUICKSTART

    $ cargo run -- id         
    $ cargo run -- selftest   
    
selftest spins up two independent identities, completes a real Noise_IKpsk2
handshake over an in-memory transport, and verifies an encrypted IP packet makes
it across intact.

:: INSTALL

needs Rust ≥ 1.85, root, and the full feature

    $ cargo build --release --features full
    $ sudo ./target/release/meshguard serve

on another machine:

    $ sudo ./target/release/meshguard connect <NodeId>

then: ping 10.x.y.z 

